# CSS !important
## Definition
The `!important` rule gives a CSS property the highest priority and overrides normal specificity rules.
## Syntax
```css
selector {
    property: value !important;
}
```
## Example
```css
p {
    color: blue;
}
#title {
    color: red;
}
p {
    color: green !important;
}
```
```html
<p id="title">Hello World</p>
```
Result:
```text
Hello World → Green
```
Even though the ID selector has higher specificity, `!important` wins.
---
## When to Use
- Override third-party CSS.
- Override framework styles (Bootstrap, Tailwind, etc.).
- Force a style when specificity becomes difficult to manage.
---
## When NOT to Use
- Avoid using it for regular styling.
- Excessive use makes CSS difficult to maintain and debug.
---
## Priority Order
```text
!important
↓
Inline Styles
↓
ID Selectors
↓
Class Selectors
↓
Element Selectors
```
## Example with Inline Style

```css
p {
    color: red !important;
}
```
```html
<p style="color: blue;">Hello</p>
```
Result:
```text
Red
```
`!important` overrides the normal inline style.
---
## Easy Memory Trick
```text
!important > Inline > ID > Class > Element
```
## One-Line Definition

`!important` gives a CSS declaration the highest priority, overriding normal specificity and cascade rules.
